title: For Sale:  1942 SAKO Finnish M39 Mosin Nagant & ammo
postcontent:
Selling the whole package, rifle, ammo, stripper clips, tool kit & ammo pouches, sightmark laser boresight, sanp caps and vintage leather sling.
Rifle is a Finnish M39, 1942 SAKO barrel, on a 1911 Izzy receiver. Stock is a wartime (rounded finger joint) unit, with some nicks and rough spots, has SAKO cartouche. Other parts are typical Finn, a mix of almost everything. Has arsenal tag with two dates (1959 &1973). I thoroughly disassembled, cleaned and inspected all parts. I have fired about 100 rounds since then, with careful cleaning after. Fires and operates nicely (for a Mosin).
Overall condition is good to very good. Most parts are still blued, barrel is bright. No corrosion or pitting. Judging by the dirt and cosmoline removed during cleaning, I think it is safe to say this rifle was never re-blued. No pits under the bluing. 
I also have 440 rounds of silver tip, steel core Soviet surplus ammo (out of the tin) and 40 rounds of Sellier & Bellot 180grain boat tail. 
No trades please, and FTF would be best as the ammo is heavy and shipping costly. I would consider shipping to an FFL if you are ok with the cost ($25 transfer fee plus actual shipping costs). and understand payment must clear prior to shipping.

title: For Sale:  M&P Shield .40 with Truglo TFO day/night sights, trigger kit and more...
postcontent:
This pistol has had roughly 100 rounds through it. It's been cleaned and oiled after use. It's the perfect balance between highly concealable (the more you worry about concealment, the less likely to carry it) and still having firepower you can have confidence in. It has an Apex trigger enhancement kit that makes a very noticeable difference in the trigger weight, smooths out the trigger break, and gives it a quicker reset. My accuracy with it jumped up to a whole 'nother level the most recent time I used it, which was the first time with the Apex kit. I have two 7 round magazines (or 7+1 if chambered) and one flush with the grip 6 round magazine (or 6+1). The sights are tritium (glows at night) and fiber optic, which you can see clearly at times that the bright sun in your eye might make usual white sights hard to see. The sights are green. I've got a kydex and leather hybrid holster w/ sweat shield to go with it (right handed) that fastens in two places about 8 or 9 inches apart, distributing the weight better. The holster hasn't been used other than trying it on when I got it. The fastening hooks can be moved up or down to change the cant (angle) of the pistol to make it more concealable or more accessible and it was molded specifically for the M&P Shield. I had planned on getting my concealed weapons permit at the time I got it all, but unfortunately things came up and the 170-some odd dollars wasn't available at the time. I now am getting ready to get it, but plan on getting a compact that is modular and can be turned into a subcompact (or full size even, though I don't need that one) as well. My full size Glock 17 I've put WAY too much work and money into to sell, so that leaves the Shield. The Shield itself shoots great. In fact, I second guessed my choice of getting it in .40 at first before I tried it out, but when I compared it at the range to my mom's 9 mm Shield and couldn't really tell a difference recoil wise. I was surprised, it's very manageable to shoot for a light .40 subcompact (even with some pretty hot ammo). The dual recoil (or guide rod) system really truly makes a difference. Even my full size gen 3 Glock 17 didn't seem a whole lot different in recoil than the Shield. Lastly, I have about 2 boxes (I think there's 38/40 rounds total) of Gold Dot SB (short barrel) 180 grain ammo to go along with it. It was designed specifically for subcompact use, so the hollowpoint expands fully at the velocity gained from a shorter barrel. The gun also has a lifetime warranty from Smith and Wesson for the original owner (the first person to register it with them), which you can still use because I have the paperwork for it still and never registered it with S&W. I also have the box, casing from the factory, lock, and booklet for it. Altogether with the Shield, extra magazine, the sights, trigger kit, holster, and ammo there's about $700 into it all and other than the pistol itself, that's not including tax or S&H. Now I'm not expecting to sell it for $700, but at the same time, it's not something I absolutely have to sell. If I get any good, fair offers then I'm sure we can work something out. $550 would be ideal, but throw me an offer. Everything will be sold together, not looking to sell bits and pieces. If you have a concealed weapons permit that's a plus, but a DL and bill of sale is a must. 

Shield - $350, after taxes and fee's about $400
Apex Tactical Duty/Carry Action Enhancement Kit (AEK) - $88
Gold Dot .40 cal Short Barrel 180 grain HP - $50, $25 per box (for self defense ammo, it's worth it)
Truglo TFO (tritium/fiber optic) M&P sights - $97.99
FoxX IWB holster - $40 roughly (inexpensive, but actually better than many that cost more)
7 round magazine - $35 average ($32-$38 depending on who's selling it)

postcontent:
When people modify Mosins they almost always screw it up...either by cheaping out on parts or what have you. I began this project to prove that you actually could build a mosin with modern flair that didn't look or shoot like it was halfassed gunsmiths bastard child. Now that I am finished with this project It's time to move on to the next.

Specs:
1924 Ishevsk Mosin Nagant Hex Receiver
Hand turned (on a Lathe) 20" Mosin barrel (was 30 something)
Target Recrowned (on same lathe)
Receiver drilled and tapped
Scoperail handmade from a 1913 picatinny blank(drilled to match bolt pattern in receiver)
Rear Iron sight removed
Nikon P-series Cantelever rings (for proper eye relief)
Bushnell 3-9x scope I had laying around
Lathe turned oversized bolt knob (I turned it)
kick back bolt handle to clear optics
knob and handle Threaded and Welded
Sits in an Archangel Chassis (with one 5 round and one 10 round mag)
Harris Bipod (not a knockoff)
Timney Trigger with thumb safety (tuned to 2.5lbs Breaks like a glass rod)
Painted Old school desert Chocolate Chip (to match a vest)


I Understand I will not get my full investment back...but for all the work and machine time I put in, I think my asking price is reasonable.
